Earlier this year, on the eve of jury selection for a trial over the 2021 A=
stroworld Festival tragedy, when a crowd crush during a Travis Scott concer=
t resulted in 10 deaths, the last of the victims=E2=80=99 families finally =
settled. But Live Nation, the event promoter, still faces outstanding claim=
s from others who were injured in the melee, and those are proving more dif=
ficult to sweep away. Instead, they=E2=80=99ve landed Live Nation before th=
e Texas Supreme Court, where the company is desperately seeking to stop a d=
eposition of its C.E.O., Michael Rapino.

It=E2=80=99s the latest legal trouble for the country=E2=80=99s biggest con=
cert promoter, which, along with Ticketmaster, is already facing a Justice =
Department suit for inflated concert prices. In the Astroworld case, the co=
urts have so far been unsympathetic to Live Nation=E2=80=99s pleas,
with both the trial judge and an appellate court clearing the way for Rapin=
o=E2=80=99s testimony. Live Nation argues that its C.E.O. lacks any insight=
 that would warrant his deposition about the disaster, framing the demand f=
or his testimony as an unwarranted intrusion into corporate affairs=E2=80=
=94exactly the sort of overreach the ostensibly business-friendly Texas cou=
rt should be guarding against.

Notably, the state=E2=80=99s highest court has made only a handful of rulin=
gs over the years concerning the so-called apex witness doctrine, which shi=
elds top executives from testifying in certain circumstances. With major co=
mpanies like Elon Musk=E2=80=99s Tesla relocating to Texas, Live Nation pre=
sented its petition as a chance to set a critical and timely precedent. The=
 justices, seemingly enticed, invited the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 attorneys to =
respond. But the maneuver may have backfired for Live Nation. The plaintiff=
s seized the opportunity this week, detailing what discovery has revealed
about Rapino=E2=80=99s participation, from his hands-on role in booking Sco=
tt to his oversight of the company=E2=80=99s public response as news of the=
 fatalities hit his inbox.

According to emails revealed in the suit, Rapino was indeed deeply involved=
 in reviewing the terms of Scott=E2=80=99s booking, which included a hefty =
advance meant to cover the artist=E2=80=99s debts. The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 =
attorneys also spotlight a 2018 email forwarded by music mogul Irving Azoff=
 to Rapino, relaying concerns from a New Orleans festival producer who deem=
ed booking Scott =E2=80=9Ctoo big a risk,=E2=80=9D citing a past incident w=
here Scott caused a riot by shouting =E2=80=9CFuck the police=E2=80=9D duri=
ng a concert. Despite these warnings, Rapino was bullish about Scott, even =
musing about working with him on TV and movie projects. In an email to a Li=
ve Nation employee=E2=80=94the eventual tour manager=E2=80=94Rapino wrote: =
=E2=80=9CI think Travis is a big star [=E2=80=A6] His raging concert style =
is one of a kind.=E2=80=9D

The plaintiffs
also aim to grill Rapino about his direct communications with Scott, celebr=
ating the packed show in texts, and later, over the phone, grappling with i=
ts aftermath. They also plan to question why, amid obvious and escalating r=
isks, the concert was allowed to proceed, citing a dispatcher=E2=80=99s omi=
nous warning to Live Nation security that night: =E2=80=9CI would want it o=
n the record that I didn=E2=80=99t advise this to continue. Someone is goin=
g to end up dead.=E2=80=9D

Despite the mounting death toll, Rapino initially wavered on canceling the =
festival=E2=80=99s second day, attempting to gauge the fallout. =E2=80=9CLe=
t=E2=80=99s wait for confirmation on deaths,=E2=80=9D he wrote in an email =
to colleagues. =E2=80=9CIf 5 died we would cancel.=E2=80=9D

In their filings, the plaintiffs underscore that, contrary to Live Nation=
=E2=80=99s claims, this email and additional evidence point to Rapino as a =
key decision-maker. They=E2=80=99re pushing hard to put him under oath and =
challenge the narrative that his involvement was
