x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Earlier this year, =
on the eve of jury selection for a trial over the 2021 Astroworld Festival =
tragedy, when a crowd crush during a <b>Travis Scott </b>concert resulted i=
n 10 deaths, the last of the victims=E2=80=99 families finally settled. But=
 Live Nation, the event promoter, still faces outstanding claims from other=
s who were <i>injured</i> in the melee, and those are proving more difficul=
t to sweep away. Instead, they=E2=80=99ve landed Live Nation before the Tex=
as Supreme Court, where the company is desperately seeking to stop a deposi=
tion of its C.E.O., <b>Michael Rapino</b>.<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s the latest=
 legal trouble for the country=E2=80=99s biggest concert promoter, which, a=
long with Ticketmaster, is already facing a Justice Department suit for inf=
lated concert prices. In the Astroworld case, the courts have so far been u=
nsympathetic to Live Nation=E2=80=99s pleas,
with both the trial judge and an appellate court clearing the way for Rapin=
o=E2=80=99s testimony. Live Nation argues that its C.E.O. lacks any insight=
 that would warrant his deposition about the disaster, framing the demand f=
or his testimony as an unwarranted intrusion into corporate affairs=E2=80=
=94exactly the sort of overreach the ostensibly business-friendly Texas cou=
rt should be guarding against. <br/><br/>Notably, the state=E2=80=99s highe=
st court has made only a handful of rulings over the years concerning the s=
o-called apex witness doctrine, which shields top executives from testifyin=
g in certain circumstances. With major companies like <b>Elon Musk</b>=E2=
=80=99s Tesla relocating to Texas, Live Nation presented its petition as a =
chance to set a critical and timely precedent. The justices, seemingly enti=
ced, invited the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 attorneys to respond. But the maneuver=
 may have backfired for Live Nation. The plaintiffs seized the opportunity =
this week, detailing what discovery has revealed
about Rapino=E2=80=99s participation, from his hands-on role in booking Sco=
tt to his oversight of the company=E2=80=99s public response as news of the=
 fatalities hit his inbox. <br/><br/>According to emails revealed in the su=
it, Rapino was indeed deeply involved in reviewing the terms of Scott=E2=80=
=99s booking, which included a hefty advance meant to cover the artist=E2=
=80=99s debts. The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 attorneys also spotlight a 2018 emai=
l forwarded by music mogul <b>Irving Azoff </b>to Rapino, relaying concerns=
 from a New Orleans festival producer who deemed booking Scott =E2=80=9Ctoo=
 big a risk,=E2=80=9D citing a past incident where Scott caused a riot by s=
houting =E2=80=9CFuck the police=E2=80=9D during a concert. Despite these w=
arnings, Rapino was bullish about Scott, even musing about working with him=
 on TV and movie projects. In an email to a Live Nation employee=E2=80=94th=
e eventual tour manager=E2=80=94Rapino wrote: =E2=80=9CI think Travis is a =
big star [=E2=80=A6] His raging concert style is one of a kind.=E2=80=9D<br=
/><br/>The plaintiffs
also aim to grill Rapino about his direct communications with Scott, celebr=
ating the packed show in texts, and later, over the phone, grappling with i=
ts aftermath. They also plan to question why, amid obvious and escalating r=
isks, the concert was allowed to proceed, citing a dispatcher=E2=80=99s omi=
nous warning to Live Nation security that night: =E2=80=9CI would want it o=
n the record that I didn=E2=80=99t advise this to continue. Someone is goin=
g to end up dead.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Despite the mounting death toll, Rapino=
 initially wavered on canceling the  festival=E2=80=99s second day, attempt=
ing to gauge the fallout. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s wait for confirmation on d=
eaths,=E2=80=9D he wrote in an email to colleagues. =E2=80=9CIf 5 died we w=
ould cancel.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In their filings, the plaintiffs underscore =
that, contrary to Live Nation=E2=80=99s claims, this email and additional e=
vidence point to Rapino as a key decision-maker. They=E2=80=99re pushing ha=
rd to put him under oath and challenge the narrative that his involvement w=
as
peripheral.<br/><br/>Whatever decision the Texas Supreme Court makes could =
be significant as the state works to attract big business, including by car=
ving out an entirely new judicial circuit to handle corporate disputes. All=
owing tort lawyers to dissect a C.E.O.=E2=80=99s crisis management tactics =
and humiliate him with questions about financial calculations=E2=80=94such =
as Rapino=E2=80=99s question, after the second day of the festival was canc=
eled, =E2=80=9CHow much does Travis owe us do we have advance?=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94could undermine that pro-business agenda. <br/></td>
